               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18361128-name-400" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18361128-name-400" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18361128-name-400" type="surname" value="PORTCH"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18361128-name-400" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>JAMES PORTCH</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a policeman. On the 8th of November, about half-past six o'clock in the evening, I was on duty in High-street, Shadwell, walking about twenty yards behind the prisoner, who was passing the pro<lb></lb>secutor's shop with several others—he made a snatch at some drawers which hung at the door—he got them down, and went two or three paces, when I took him with them under his arm—I said, "Let go," and he then dropped them—there was a chain attached to them—they were in the doorway.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner. Q.</hi> Was I sober? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I consider so—he walked very well to the station-house—he snatched them down, and deliberately walked away with them.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18361128-name-401" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18361128-name-401" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18361128-name-401" type="surname" value="JEGGINS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18361128-name-401" type="given" value="JAMES JOHNSON"></interp>JAMES JOHNSON JEGGINS</persName>
                  </hi>. My son Samuel Jeggins keeps this shop—the drawers belong to him.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner's Defence.</hi> It was a very wet day, and if I had dropped them they must have been all over mud—I did not know what I had done till the morning.</p>
